$$\newcommand{\C}{\mathbb{C}} \newcommand{\R}{\mathbb{R}} \newcommand{\Z}{\mathbb{Z}} \newcommand{\Q}{\mathbb{Q}} \newcommand{\P}{\mathbb{P}} \newcommand{\F}{\mathbb{F}} \newcommand{\N}{\mathbb{N}} \newcommand{\E}{\mathbb{E}}$$

     This first part of the Jupyter, we will address the physical and theoretical underpinnings of Yan et al. (2013) [0], then in the second part we will implement our own Walk-on-Sphere (WoS) algorithm to solve a two-dimensional Laplace equation with an unit sphere domain, $D$ , and simple boundary, $\partial D$, and a three-dimensional Laplace equation with unit sphere domain$D$, and simple boundary, $\partial D$.
     The objective of Yan et al. (2013) was to proposed a hybrid approach that could approximate solutions to three-dimensional Poisson and modified Helmholtz equations at a reduced computational cost compared to conventional methods found in Boundary Elements Methods (BEMs) and Finite Element Methods (FEMs). The approach combines a locally deterministic Boundary Integral Method with a Feynman-Kac formulated solutions to elliptic Partial Differential Equations (PDEs).
     Further elaborating the authors choice a electrostatic potential problem specific to Very Large Scale Integration (VLSI) chips to implement their hybrid approach; specifically, the domain of electrostatic potential problem is the conductor, $\Omega$, and the boundary condition, $\partial \Omega$, is the surface of the conductor. The surface charge distribution $\sigma_{s}$ from Gauss's Law is equal to the normal derivative of the electrostatic potential,

$$\sigma_{s}=E \cdot n |_{\partial \Omega} = \frac{\partial u}{\partial n} |_{\partial \Omega}.$$

And since the inhomogeneous right-hand side of a Poisson, the authors were able to reduce this Poisson equation through a simple subtraction technique to a Laplace equation with a modified boundary condition. To attain the Dirichlet data one only need to approximate the solution of the Boundary Integral equation over the modified boundary condition, $\partial D$. This can be accomplished through approximating the following form,

$$u(x)=\int_{\partial \Omega} G(x,y)\frac{\partial u(y)}{\partial n_{y}} ds_{y} - \int_{\partial \Omega} \frac{\partial G(x,y)}{\partial n_{y}} u(y) ds_{y} (eq. 2.3) ,$$

simply the $n_{y}$ is the normal derivative of the boundary of $\Omega$ or $\Omega^{c}$ to which any $x \in \Omega$ or $\Omega^{c}$, and where said Green function $G(x,y)$ is the core to the approximate solution of the aforementationed Laplace equation; illustratively,

$$G(x,y)=\frac{1}{4 \pi}\frac{1}{\vert x - y \vert}.$$

     To attain the solutions of Laplace equation over the modified boundary, the authors utilized a WoS algorithm; an comparable application of the WoS algorithm could be found in Simonov (2017) [1] and Simonov (2008) [2]. But if the reader desires to attain an deeper understanding of the WoS algorithm, we would suggest they read Sawhney and Crane (2020)[3, 4], as a framework code written in compiled language C++ could be found on for solving a a two-dimensional Laplace equation [5].
     Digressing, in Yan et al. (2013, pg. B871-B873) [0], the authors outline the theoretical framework, and the practical implementation of a WoS algorithm posed to solve a Laplace equation. Most importantly the authors expounded with brevity, the role of Feynmann-Kac formula's [6] abridgement of stochastic processes and partial differential equations; in essence the through the Feynman-Kac formula the solution to the Laplace equation with modified boundary conditions is given by,

$$u(x)=E^{x}\big(\phi(X_{\tau_{\Omega}})\big)+E^{x}\bigg[ \int_{0}^{\tau_{\Omega}} f(X_{t}) dt \bigg],$$

which means that the solution is given by the expected value of the collection of Brownian motion paths that hit the modified boundary, $\partial \Omega$; given when the forcing function $f \equiv 0$. Consequentially, the previous formula becomes,

$$u(x)=E^{x}\big(\phi(X_{\tau_{\Omega}})\big)= \int_{\partial \Omega} \phi(y) d \mu_{\Omega}^{x}.$$

And simply the $\phi(y)$ is the point where a said Brownian motion path hits the boundary $\partial \Omega$, and $\mu_{\Omega}^{x}$ the respective probability that that event occurring.
     Subsequentially the authors proceeded to the attainment of the Neumann data that is required in this Hybrid approach, Yan et al. (2013,pg. 876-877); the authors applied eq. 2.3 over the arbitrary superimposed hemisphere, $\Omega_{S}$, on the boundary condition, $\partial \Omega$, of the space $\Omega$; it yielded

$$u(x)=-\int_{\Gamma} \frac{\partial G(x,y)}{\partial n_{y}} u(y) ds_{y}+\int_{S} \bigg[ \frac{\partial G(x,y)}{\partial n_{y}} u(y)+G(x,y)\frac{\partial u(y)}{\partial n_{y}} \bigg] ds_{y}, x \in \Omega_{S} (eq. 4.1).$$

Consequentially by solving eq. 4.1 for $u(x)$, we can attain the Neumann data over the domain $S$, which is what was being sought in this process. And similarly to attaining the Dirichlet data, the authors of Yan et al. (2013) suggested to the reader that they should consider utilizing a WoS algorithm to solve eq 4.1. In essence one needs to form said linear algebraic system,

$$K\bigg[ \frac{\partial u}{\partial n} \bigg](x) = b(x), x \in S,$$

where,

$$K\bigg[ \frac{\partial u}{\partial n} \bigg]=\int_{S} G(x,y)\frac{\partial u(y)}{\partial n_{y}}ds_{y},$$

and,

$$b(x)=\bigg[ \frac{u(x)}{2}+\int_{S} \frac{\partial G(x,y)}{\partial n_{y}} u(y)ds_{y}\bigg]+\int_{\Gamma} \frac{\partial G(x,y)}{\partial n_{y}} u(y)ds_{y}.$$

Then form the well-condition form of said system found in eq. 4.6, eq. 4.7 and eq. 4.8; then solving said well-conditioned system with an iterative solver. In essence this is the entirety of the computational method named Boundary Integral Equation-Walk-on-Sphere (BIE-WoS); in addition, the authors outlined the algorithm in the following description.

BIE-WoS Algorithm.The BIE-WoS method for Neumann data over a patch $S$ consists of the following steps

  • Step 1. Apply the Feynmann-Kac formula (eq. 2.9) using the WoS sampling technique to compute the right-hand-side function $b(x)$ in (eq. 4.4) or (eq. 4.8) by appropriate Gauss quadratures.

  • Step 2. Solve the BIE (eq. 4.2) or (eq. 4.6) with a collocation method to obtain the Neumann data $\frac{\partial u}{\partial n}$ over S.

     As aformentationed by the authors, after the Neumann data is attained, the eq. 2.3 from Yan et al. (2013, eq. 2.3, pg. B870) can be used to the electrostatic potential over the whole space.

     The first implemention of our WoS algorithm will pertain to a non-mixed BVP of the two-dimension Laplace equation over a unit cirle domain, $D=[-1,1] \times [-1,1]$, with $u(x)=f(x)$ on the boundary, $\partial D$. Our second implementation will pertain to a non-mixed BVP of the three-dimension Laplace equaton over a unit sphere domain, $D=[-1,1] \times [-1,1] \times [-1,1] \equiv [-1,1]^{3}$, with $u(x,y)=f(x,y)$ on the boundary, $\partial D$.
     Let begin we the first implementation; the two-dimension Laplace equation,

$$\bigtriangleup u(x)=0 \text{ for } x \in \R^{2}.$$

The Boundary value problem for Laplace equation is represented as,

$$ \begin{cases} \frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial x^{2}} + \frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial y^{2}}=0, & \mbox{ in domain } D\\ u(x)=f(x), & \mbox{ on boundary } \partial D \end{cases}.$$

To illustrate the unit circle domain, we included the following image.

     To begin with implementation, we only need to import numpy as np, matplotlib.pyplot as plt, scipy.stats as stats and functions Point and line from sympy. In fact the implementation of a Walk-on-Sphere algorithm does not require many Python packages, and the most technical component of the algorithm is the Brownian motion algorithm contained in the algorithm itself that generates the independent and identically (i.i.d) distributed random normal sphere walk that maps the boundary.
     To generate the Brownian motion paths, we utilized Algoritm 5.17 (Generating Brownian motion) from Handbook of Monte Carlo Methods by Dirk P. Kroese, Thomas Taimre and Zdravko I. Botev (2011, pg. 182) [7, 8], and implemented the algorithm in Python. To generate the standard normal random variable denoted in Kroese et al. (2011, pg. 182), $Z_{t}=\big( W_{t}, \ldots, W_{t_{n}}\big)$, we choice to utilize the Box-Muller transform method [9].
     To test our Python implementation of Algoritm 5.17, we choice time to be 1 second, e.g. t=1, with ten-thousand sampled steps.

U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,n);
U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,n);
X=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 

t=1; h=np.sqrt(t/n);

DW=h*X;
W=np.zeros(n+1);
W[1:]=np.cumsum(DW);
plt.ylabel("Range of Brownian Motion")
plt.xlabel("Steps");

     As one can observe, one-dimensional Brownian motion is insufficient for an two-dimensioned WoS algorithm, as the direction of motion is limited to forward advancemeant along the horizontal-axis, and therefore does not possess the full-directional versatility of two-dimension Brownian motion.
     To implement two-dimensioned Brownian motion, we only need to generate an additional Brownian motion path in the y-direction to give the desired variation and advancement in the vertical-axis. To generate this additional Brownian motion path, we reused the Box-Muller transformation second transform to generate a second standard normal random variable, which was passed through Algorithm 5.17 to generate the path.

     Central to our focus, we can finally implement our WoS algorithm. Though to experiment, we will first implement a random walk algorithm, so to compared its result's with the WoS algorithm's.
     Our random walk algorithm is composed of two Python functions, simulate_exit_time(w,n,t) and check_exit; the first function is the core of the algorithm where the Brownian motion is generated, the second function is the termination function, when the Brownian motion hits the boundary condition.
     The following implementation is in regards to a unit sphere domain, $D$, which has a simple boundary, $\partial D$.

In [81]:
def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w) >=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    i=0; temp=0;
    while not exit:
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        y=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y
        exit=check_exit(x);
        if exit==False:
            r=1-np.linalg.norm(x);
            circle1=plt.Circle(x,radius=r,fill=False);
            plt.gcf().gca().add_artist(circle1);
            plt.axis([-1.2, 1.2, -1.2, 1.2]);
        if np.linalg.norm(temp)!=0:
            x_val=[temp[0],x[0]]; y_val=[temp[1],x[1]];
            plt.plot(x_val,y_val);
        plt.text(x[0],x[1],'x'+str(i+1));
        i=i+1;
        temp=x;
    return x;

     Though the position is initialize at w=np.array((0,0)), the actual initialization point is set from the first Brownian motion sample. Similar to the our previous implementation of two-dimensional Brownian motion, we set time to one second, t=1; though for this experiment we set the partition number to eight, n=8, so that the resulting plot could remain legible.

     Observing the result, one can discern that a random walk algorithm take several steps prior to hitting the boundary condition, $\partial D$. This means there exists a probablistic computational overhead that can vary depending on the optimality of the Brownian motion path that develops. This computational overhead can increase in the worst case scenario, such as, in Example #2 - Unlucky Case, or it can remain constant (e.g. the same) in the case of Example #1 - Lucky Case.

def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w) >=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    while not exit:
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        y=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y
        exit=check_exit(x);
    return x;

     Proceeding, we will finally simulate our random walk algorithm: we decided upon time scale of one second with two-thousand partitions. With that, we decided to generate ten-thousand Brownian motion pathways. In addition we choice to time, so to compare its computational cost to a WoS algorithm. We accomplished this task with incorporation of process_time from the time package, which captures the time it executes, so we were able to capture the CPU process time of our random walk algorithm.
     With a n=2000 partition of the time scale $t$, we gave these Brownian motion paths a finer time scaled then the previous example; it effect, we introduced a greater variation into the algorithm. In essence a Brownian motion that possesses a finer partition of the time scale, subsequentially possesses a smaller size step, as each Brownian motion sample - aka step size is proportioned with the square root of the time scale's partition size, $\Delta t$, which is the standard deviation of the normal distribution that the Brownian motion step is being drawn (or sampled) from. Recollection, a standard normal random variable, $Z=\mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=1)$, can be transformed into another non-standard normal, $X$, given the following transformation,

$$X=\sigma Z+\mu.$$

We can prove this transformation simply,

$$E[X]=E[\sigma Z + \mu]=\sigma E[Z] + \mu= \sigma \cdot 0 + \mu = \mu,$$

and,

$$Var[X]=Var[\sigma Z + \mu] = \sigma^{2} Var[Z] + 0 = \sigma^{2} \cdot 1 = \sigma^{2}.$$

Consequentially each Brownian motion sample, $B_{t}$, is from a normal distribution, $B_{t}=\mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=\sqrt{\Delta t})$. With key fact in mind, one can discern that a smaller step size means that the sample of said step originates from a normal with a small variance, which cause the Brownian motion step to be lessed variated. But due to the increase in the number of sampled that can be drawn from $\mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=\sqrt{\Delta t})$ with a finer time scale mesh, it variation seems to be greater then a Brownian motion that possesses a less fine time scale mesh. Though this additional variation increases the propensity of the Brownian motion pathways to tend to the worst case scenario, as the smaller step size allows for a greater propensity for a Brownian path to wonder inside the domain, resulting in perhap a needless incease in the computational overhead of the algorithm.
     Though we will discuss this further in a bit. Mean while, let proceed with experimentation, we choice partition of the time scale of n=2000, and decide to generate ten-thousand Brownian motion paths.

     Nevertheless the resulting approximate solution of $u(x)$ that is attained possessess an error of $10^{-2}$, which can be improved with an increase in the number of Brownian motion paths generated, or an increase in the number of pertitions, e.g., n > 200. Indeed both the size of the partitions of the time scale and the number of Brownian motion paths generated determines accuracy and the variation of the probability distribution of estimate solutions of $u(x)$ that are attained when executing this algorithm. To clarify, the estimation of $u(x)$ that is attained is an estimate paremeter, and as such this estimate possess a bais (e.g. a error) to it, which seperates it from the true paramete, e.g., the exact solution of $u(x)$.
     To properly illustrate this statistical phenomenon, we had to construct two additional experiments specific to this inquiry. In both experiments we sought to attain a confidence interval for the estimate parameter, which in this context is the estimated solution to $u(x)$. From the collected estimates, we were able to calculate sample mean, sample standard deviation, and thus the Confidence Interval of the estimated parameter. [10,11]

     Proceeding to our second implementation, non-mixed BVP of the three-dimension Laplace equaton over a unit sphere domain, $D=[-1,1] \times [-1,1] \times [-1,1] \equiv [-1,1]^{3}$, with $u(x,y)=f(x,y)$ on the boundary, $\partial D$.

$$\bigtriangleup u(x,y)=0 \text{ for } x,y \in \R^{3}.$$

The Boundary value problem for Laplace equation is represented as,

$$ \begin{cases} \frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial x^{2}} + \frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial y^{2}} + \frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial z^{2}}=0, & \mbox{ in domain } D\\ u(x,y)=f(x,y), & \mbox{ on boundary } \partial D \end{cases}.$$

     Extending the random walk algorithm to a third dimension, only required a slight modification to our two-dimensional implementatin.

def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w) >=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    i=0;
    W=np.zeros((n+1000,3));
    while not exit:
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,3);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,3);
        y=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y;
        exit=check_exit(x);
        W[i,:]=x;
        i=i+1;
    # print(W);
    ax=plt.axes(projection='3d');
    ax.plot3D(W[:,0],W[:,1],W[:,2],'gray');
    plt.figure().set_size_inches(18.5, 10.5)
    plt.show();
    return x;

As anticipated the estimated parameter $u(x,y)$ improved significantly in accuracy with the inclusion of a third-dimension; this statistical phenomenon can be explaid by the Strong Law of Large Numbers [12,13], as stated in the law,

$$\bar{Y}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} X_{i} \to \mu \text{ as } n \to \infty$$

and,

$$\text{Var}\big(\bar{Y}\big)=\text{Var}\big(\frac{1}{n}\big(X_{1}+\cdots+X_{n}\big)\big)=\frac{1}{n^{2}}\text{Var}\big(X_{1}+\cdots+X_{n}\big)=\frac{n\sigma^{2}}{n^{2}}=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}$$,

given $X_{1},\ldots, X_{n}$ were independent and identically distributed random variables with a population mean $\mu$ and population variance $sigma^{2}$. Peeling back, this subsequentially means our estimate parameter for the test function $u(x)$ will continuously improve with an increase in partitions of the time scale, n, or an increase in the number of Brownian motions path generated, or the addition of an additional dimension. This schema improve in computational efficiency and accuracy with an increase in the increase of sampling and dimension complexity of the problem itself; which is a profound and useful feature of this schema. To ground this assertion, one should note that our two-dimensional random walk algorithm took 13.28125 seconds to be computed, while the three dimensional random walk algorithm took half the time, 6.03125 seconds - which is a substantial quantity of computational savings, and this is what contributes to this schema interests and effect.
     The Walk-on-Sphere algorithm is an random walk algorithm itself,though it incorporate a computational saving technique known as sphere walking, which allows the algorithm to jump across its Brownian motion path without explicitly generating by superimposing a cirle in two-dimension, sphere in three-dimension, or a hyper-dimensioned sphere in n-dimensions greater than three, to jump from the first sampled of the Brownian motion path to the boundary condition, $\partial D$. Though this reduction in computational complexity does come without a cost, the reduction in the Brownian motion path's capacity to wonder results in an increase in the estimate parameter variance, which is not desire by the least, but is a price to be paid; nevertheless we will further elaborate about this matter in the coming section.
     To modify two-dimensioned random walk algorithm to a two-dimensioned WoS algorithm, we only needed to include, x=x+np.random.uniform(-1,1,2)*(1-np.linalg.norm(x));, which performs the sphere walk that generates the computational saving. In addition, as the sphere walk might make the Brownian motion path land on the boundary, $\partial D$, or pass it, and need to include an additional boundary check function, e.g., exit=check_exit(x);, which could test for this event.

def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w) >=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    i=0; temp=0;
    while not exit:
        x=x+np.random.uniform(-1,1,2)*(1-np.linalg.norm(x));
        exit=check_exit(x);
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        y=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y;
        exit=check_exit(x);
        if exit==False:
            r=1-np.linalg.norm(x);
            circle1=plt.Circle(x,radius=r,fill=False);
            plt.gcf().gca().add_artist(circle1);
            plt.axis([-1.2, 1.2, -1.2, 1.2]);

            x_val=[temp[0],x[0]]; y_val=[temp[1],x[1]];
            plt.plot(x_val,y_val);
        plt.text(x[0],x[1],'x'+str(i));
        i=i+1;
        temp=x;
    return x;

Though if the time scale mesh is given to be fine, i.e., n=2000, the fewer Brownian motion paths needed to be generated to attain a substantially lower variance when compared to a less fine time scale mesh and more Brownian motion path generated. Overall the finer time scale mesh attains a tigher confidence interval, compared to the opposite paradigm.
     An additional price of the WoS algorithm is that, the algorithm sphere walk is domain boundary sensitive, as each different type of boundary condition require a different size sphere to be superimposed over the Brownian motion path to sphere hop. In case of the unit circle, the optimal radius of the cirle is 0.90-np.linalg.norm(x) and not 1-np.linalg.norm(x), as the former approach hops the Brownian motion path closer to the boundary condition, $\partial D$, when the path reachs ourside the domain $D$.

In [111]:
def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w)>=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    while not exit:
        x=x+np.random.uniform(-1,1,2)*(0.90-np.linalg.norm(x));
        exit=check_exit(x);
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,2);
        y=np.sqrt(-3*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y;
        exit=check_exit(x);
    return x;

As anticipated from previous results in this Jupyter Notebook, the increase in the capicity for the Brownian motion path to wonder contributes to a overall lower variation in the estimated parameter. Specifically a smaller step size due to many more partitions, result in more Brownian motion samples, e.g. steps. With a smaller sphere jump, also will contribute to the Brownian motion wondering longer inside the domain, contributing to a higher internal variation, but also a greater sample size - so to provide more information for the latter calculation of the estimated parameter. In consequence the higher internal variation leads to a smaller variation in the estimated parameter for $u(x)$, which is exactly was we hoped for.
     As observed the confidence interval is significantly tighter then other previous algorithm implementations; this is because of the reduce variation in the estimated parameter.
     In the same way as two-dimension random walk algorithm for the two-dimensioned Laplace equation, we will modify the three-dimension random walk algorithm into the three-dimension WoS algorithm for the three-dimensioned Laplace equation. Yet again the modification was quite simple, we only needed to include x=x+np.random.uniform(-1,1,3)*(1-np.linalg.norm(x)); and an additional boundary check function exit=check_exit(x);.

def check_exit(w):
    if np.linalg.norm(w) >=1:
        return True;
    return False;

def simulate_exit_time(w,n,t):
    h=np.sqrt(t/n);
    exit=False;
    x=w.copy();
    while not exit:
        x=x+np.random.uniform(-1,1,3)*(1-np.linalg.norm(x));
        exit=check_exit(x);
        U1=np.random.uniform(0,1,3);
        U2=np.random.uniform(0,1,3);
        y=np.sqrt(-2*np.log(U1))*np.cos(2*np.pi*U2); 
        x=x+h*y
        exit=check_exit(x);
    return x;

     This final experiment end our inquiry on the Walk-on-Sphere algorithm in this Jupyter Notebook, though many more interesting inquiry can be explored with this stochastic numerical schema, especially pertaining to more irregular domains and boundary conditions.

     Ding et al. (2022) [15] is the natural evolution of Yan et al. (2013) [0], the authors further developed their hybrid-algorithm, the Walk-on-Sphere (WoS) - Boundary Integral Equation (BIE) algorithm, which can approximate global solutions to a large variety of mixed type Boundary Value Problems (BVPs) of the Laplace equations. Though the mechination are far more developed in this paper Ding et al. (2022) [15],then in Yan et al. (2013) [0]. Example of the research efforts maturity is the flow-chart that pertain to the WoS-BIE algorithm, which details the various steps in the computation process. Lastly the numerical result from the WoS-BIE algorithm are quite fascinating, and quite worthy of review; overall Ding et al. (2022) [15] is well-created.
